    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-02-23T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-02-23T17:00:00-05:00" n="576"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d576">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.00111 <hi rend="superscript">Lic. Wolf,
                        Rudolf/51</hi>/57: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-02-23T22:00:00+00:00"
                            >February 23, 1937—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 23—4 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>264. Embassy’s telegram No. 240, February 18, 8 [<hi rend="italic">9</hi>] p.m.
                    Consul at Havre reports that the 17 planes which arrived on the steamer <hi
                        rend="italic">Waalhaven</hi> have been sold to the Société Française de
                    Transports Aeriens which will instruct what disposition is to be made of
                    them.</p>
                <p>Upon investigation it appears that this company was formed in September last year
                    with a capital of 100,000 francs and that its present manager is Edouard
                    Godillot (see Embassy’s telegram No. 70, January 16, 3 p.m.) with offices in
                    Paris. The firm has a doubtful reputation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
